Notes:

Date:  0/0/1902
Source:  Settler's Handbook of NZ, The
Author:
Vol / Page:  262
Edition:
Quote:   The formation is chiefly Upper Palaeozoic and Upper Mesozoic rocks. 244,000 acres, mainly in the back country, are covered with bush, chiefly tawhai, tawhai rauriki, and tawhai raunui, the last being found along the shores of Lake Sumner and the banks of the Hurunui River, and, with the exception of the tawhai raunui, is of little value for timber purposes.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1906
Source:  Manual NZ Flora
Author:  CHEESEMAN
Vol / Page:  643
Edition:
Quote:  <i>F. Solandri, Hook.f. </i>... A lofty forest-tree 40-60 ft. high; ... bark black ... in old trees ... pale and smooth on young ones; ... Leaves ... clothed with an appressed greyish-white pubescence beneath ... usually in hilly or mountain districts. ... <i>Tawhai; Tawhai-rauriki; Black-birch; White-birch</i>. ... Wood pale-red, often streaked with black, not durable ...

<i>N. cliffortioides </i>...<i>F. Cliffortioides, Hook.f.</i> ... A small tree, usually from 20 ft. to 40 ft. high ... Mountain districts ... <i>Tawhai-rauriki; Mountain Beech</i> or <i>Birch. </i>
